segments.text: testing one two three testing testing testing testing one two three testing this is july the sixth and out at still waters the home of ken and anne pierce to chat about his student days uh
Begin, please, Ken, introduce yourself to anybody that might hear this tape or read a transcription.
Give a biographical summary before you got to A&M.
Where'd you grow up?
What did mom and dad do?
Where'd you go to high school?
Anything else you did of any importance before coming to A&M?
Well, I was born in Snyder, Texas, and began elementary school in Hobbs, New Mexico,
and moved to Brownwood, Texas, and lived there until my ninth grade, middle of my ninth grade year, and we moved to a farm in Fisher County, north of Robie, between Robie and Rotan.
And I stayed there until I graduated from high school and came to A&M around the first of June, 1951.
Mom and dad, what was your dad's profession?
My dad ran a restaurant or ran cafes or restaurants, and he was a cook.
But did you all end up farming?
Yes.
During the time that we lived in Fisher County, well, this had been a dream of his for many years.
Going into the restaurant business was a necessity.
Born of the drought and drought conditions and the depression years of the early 30s in Scurry County.
And he had, his family lost their farm at that time.
And so this was something that he, a way for him to have a paycheck, meager paycheck in the Skurry County.
And he always dreamed of going back to the farm.
And then after he got back to the farm, well,
He had two boys that were approaching college age and he decided, well, the farm income might not be enough to get them educated.
In both philosophical and real terms, why did you attend A&M?
Why did you go to college?
Whose idea was it and so forth?
Well, going to college was something that my mother had always
really hammered at me on.
She went to East Texas State and was very adamant that her children would go to college.
My dad did not finish high school, but he valued education from the other vantage of not having it and being
very determined that his boys would have.
And I had become interested in veterinary medicine.
I really liked Texas Tech, which was the closest big school to us where we lived on the farm.
But after
I really decided that I was going to try to become a veterinarian while the vet school was at A&M, so that seemed the most reasonable place to go.
Before you came to enroll, had you visited A&M?
Yes, I'd been here two or three years in the spring for FFA events.
I was involved in judging teams in high school, and I was fortunate enough to be on judging teams at the state level in state competition a couple of those years.
What impression had A&M made on you, those visits?
Well, it seemed like a very friendly place.
We stayed in the dorm, having contacts with a couple of boys from Fisher County.
And they would make arrangements for us to stay near them.
And of course, there seemed to be a lot
good activities going on among the students all the time, and it was really a big place to me.
Those were the main things, I guess, that I remember.
We're not trying to put Tech down or build it up, but as far as you knew, how did those two compare in reputation and so forth?
You mentioned Tech before.
Well, my impression was that A&M was kind of a different tier.
I would have thought of McMurray College and Hardin-Simmons as being one level, and then Texas Tech would be another level, and then A&M would be one of the big schools.
It really wasn't that big a school at that time.
When you came to enroll, how did you get here?
Who'd you come with?
What did you bring?
Describe that whole trip.
I graduated, well, first let me say that I came for summer school in 1951.
This was either the only year
are one of two consecutive years that an experiment was run at A&M to have CORE for credit for freshmen in the summer.
And it's kind of an, I guess, an exploration of whether this would be a way to accelerate, possibly accelerate a program
for students at A&M since it was an all military school and it did, a person really couldn't gain and accelerate just by going to summer school because you couldn't get the ROTC off.
So I graduated from high school and I believe it was about eight days later
Well, my dad and another father, Mr. Herman, brought two boys down here.
And they're the Herman Buick.
So they had a big roadmaster that we rode down in in style.
What did you bring, as far as you can recall?
What stuff?
Well, I knew that the uniforms would be provided, and we did, each of us had a footlocker.
We'd gotten that information, and Mr. Herman was in the clothing business in Winters, Texas, and we, so he had ordered
a good footlocker for each one of us that would have the proper dimensions and everything.
And he had gotten some khaki, a couple of khaki shirts for each of us.
We each had a couple of khaki shirts and some khakis and just sheets and towels and things.
Anyway, it was all in that footlocker.
whatever I took was just clothing items.
And I don't remember bringing anything else.
No radio?
No.
And no record player of any sort?
No.
And when you got here, how did you find your dormitory, your outfit, and that sort of thing?
How did you get placed?
Well...

we stopped at the Aggieland Inn and there was a sign there pointing in it was a handmade sort of a sign to check where people were to check in and to get their directions and the freshmen that year that summer for summer school the freshmen were to live in the dorms

fourteen and uh... fifteen i may be a little it's either fourteen i know it was fourteen because that was the air force dorm and i lived in fourteen and it was either fifteen or seventeen that was the uh... the uh... army dorm army corps dorm and uh... so
there were four dorms over there and at that time there was also another, well there was Walton Hall and another small

building that really wasn't a dorm i don't think but it was used to house some of the upperclassmen but uh all right so y'all did you spent the night in uh aggie land or did you just drive in and go we we just it was being used at that time it
As far as I know, it was full of the student activities and those type of things.
It was all offices as far as I could see at that time.
But we got our instructions on where to go, and so our parents helped us move in.
Our dads helped us get our things in.
And I think Wilford had Herman, the boy, had a fan to real force that to bring it down because
We really needed it.
Do you remember what floor y'all were on?
The first place, the very first room we had was on the first floor.
Oh, so that was a warmer.
Yeah, and it was on the north side so it would have been away from no breeze at all.
And we got in and these two really nice upperclassmen stopped by and introduced themselves to our dads and just
all smiles and, you know, boy, we were just thinking, what a nice place.
Boy, these are a couple of real nice upperclassmen going to help us out, you know, and everything.
So then our dads left after just a little while.
Do you remember anything your dad said to you during those last few hours that stuck in your heart, your mind?
No, I really don't.
How much money did you have in your pocket, reckon?
I don't remember that.
Maybe 20, I just don't remember.
It wasn't very much money, though.
And do you have any idea what a semester or a year cost?
No, I don't.
But, of course, tuition was $25 a semester.
And you're not one of these whose father gave him so many acres to farm for four years, and whatever he produced, that would be his college?
No.
Okay.
Eddie Joe Davis, that happened to him up in Jacksboro.
For four years, that was what he was to do.
All right, so the father's left.
Yeah.
And we had been sort of straightening things out, you know, and decided it was already hot, being one of the first few days in June.
So we kind of decided we'd lie down on the mattress before we made it up or anything.
And we were lying there, and these same two nice upperclassmen came in.
And boy, it hit the fan in a hurry then.
So our education began at that point, I'd say.
And what kind of orientation activities did those upperclassmen inflict?
I remember that we were lying there and just kind of casually said, hi guys, or something like that, to that effect.
And boy, one of them just bellowed out, you know, freshman, on your feet.
And...
hit a brace, and of course I didn't know what a brace was or anything, so they had to start from scratch.
Then you go to, you eat at Duncan?
No, Sabisa.
Sabisa, and did y'all, as far as you recall, did you fall in to march to the first meal?
Yeah, in a manner of speaking, and
I've been trying to remember, think back on the sequence of this as to when the upperclassmen came in.
But as best I remember, we had, I think we came in on one day, which meant then we marched to Chow that evening and the next morning.
And that night, the first night, we were in the hall most of the evening.
learning what we weren't to do and what we were to do.
And after breakfast the next morning, well, we got our uniforms, walked over.
We were marched over.
And this was just east of Sabeasa.
behind Milner Hall in that area that is now the cooling tower, right on that same area where the cooling tower is as I remember it.
Of your uniforms, about what portion of your uniforms were new and what part were used, had turned by somebody else that had been turned in?
I think
Everything was used, I think.
And so from then on, you're in full uniform.
Yeah.
And learning how to shine brass and shine and polish our shoes to everyone's satisfaction.
Of course, we had a little bit of time.

uh... in the middle or early after lunch we were instructed to if we didn't have our shoe polish and brasso and things like that there were stores at north gate that we could go get same and so we did some of that anyway how long before paddle was in use well
We did not have a paddle that summer.
It was in the fall that I had my first experience with it.
There was a lot of monitoring, I guess, since this was a new program.
And what courses did you take?
Do you remember?
I took chemistry.
in organic chemistry, English.
That's already a tough load.
You had had chemistry in high school?
Yeah, those were the two courses.
You'd had chemistry in high school?
No.
Oh, you had not?
No.
What was it like then?
really, really scary.
And this was my first experience, and I'm not saying this to sound bragging or anything, but especially when I was going to school at Robie, I just didn't study.
It wasn't necessary.
And I made, you know,
Pretty good grades, good grades.
But of course I came to A&M on probation because that was a little school that I didn't take enough acceptable courses for full admission to A&M.
And yet here I was confronted with something and it was, for the first couple weeks, it was just an out of control situation.
I'd never experienced that before.
Do you remember who the chemistry teacher was?
Oh, yeah.
Well, I can't remember his name.
Wasn't one of the legendary, John Beckham or somebody like that?
No.
This was a man who died during our freshman year.
He was killed in a boating accident, as I remember.
Seemed like he was involved.
He was doing research with the oceanography group.
You were here all summer?
Yeah.
About how many students were?
Well, there were two Air Force squadrons in dorm 14, and there were two companies, infantry companies.
Well, one infantry and one artillery, I believe.
As you remember them?
Of course, there were many, many, many,
sophomores and other upperclassmen, but especially sophomores.
See, at that particular time, there were two types of people that went to summer school at A&M.
There were students who flunked a course or one or more courses and had to make up the slack.
Or they were graduate students who were here a lot of

you know right graduate students teachers and that type of people and they were living in a remote location to us they were just in another world as far as i knew at that time but there were so many sophomores as as you recall describe the routine of a day what time did y'all get up what did you do how long were classes
Did you have Reveille and fallout and all that?
Yeah, we fell out.
I can't remember.
I think we fell out at 7.
No, it wasn't because we started classes.
We had 7 o'clock classes.
So we fell out at 6.
Because that beat the heat to have the 7 o'clock class.
And we really needed it because there were no air-conditioned classes.
that time.
And the classes lasted about how long?
I think they lasted an hour and a half hour and 15 minutes for an hour and a half.
Then you had chemistry lab every day?
No I think it was three days two three days a week and then one afternoon was ROTC was drill
And we had a PE class and ROTC.
Those were the things, the classes that we attended.
And these two Air Force companies, were most of them fish?
Yeah.
All of the people, all of the members of each of the squadrons and companies were freshmen.
except for a CO and an executive officer, two seniors and two juniors.
Yeah, so you all didn't have the task that you would have in the fall of cleaning up an upperclassman's room every morning.
You didn't have to do that.
No.
But in the dining hall, did you all have the same kind of routine that summer that would be in the fall?
Yeah, uh-huh.
And we were exposed to various things, items of foolishness associated with the dining hall.
There was one of the juniors who

convened an order of the green dragon i guess and he'd do all sorts of foolish things i mean it was it was just a shirt something to to uh make the freshmen do foolish things such as uh oh you'd have to he would uh when he would convene this and it it didn't involve the same people but uh

when he would convene the Order of the Green Dragon, he'd borrow one of the waiter's trays, and he would just come up to a table with the freshmen still there, and at the freshmen table, you know, there are 10 tables would seat 10 people, and so we would have
all eight freshmen, typically there'd be eight freshmen on the table.
And then if there were upperclassmen sitting, well, there'd be at least one upperclassman at one end or the other.
And often there'd be two upperclassmen, one at each end.
But we thought it was pretty bad, all the things we had to go through it that summer.
But really, it wasn't that bad because we didn't have sophomores in the picture.

sitting with us because we did see the the upperclassmen they were going to summer school ate some in another part of Sabisa but this guy is our I can't remember his name for sure I can see his face but he would come in he would come to your table and he would bong so many times on the on the metal tray the big
aluminum tray and convene the Order of the Green Dragon and he would point to this one or that one and to go over and he'd give you a table to go sing something, you know.
So nothing bad?
No, it was the main thing was just I guess he enjoyed seeing how people would

how you know a function under in the embarrassed so you're in chemistry and english class just about all morning then lab or rotc most of the afternoon then at night were you back in your room studying and so how did uh how did the summer go in terms of uh academically for you

well you mean the grades yeah you did okay i did all right but i started i went into the hole in chemistry pretty to begin with but then i i had a couple of of uh freshmen around me who had had found chemistry to be easy in high school and they hardly studied made a point of it in fact one of them jimmy smith i remember him quite well because we were
of buddied up and he he really helped me out with chemistry but he kind of made a show of the fact that he he knew this chemistry no problem and he would he didn't study much well we both made bees
I made B the first semester, the first six weeks to take.
So you pulled out of that hole quickly.
Well, we just finished the one semester of the first semester.
Isn't that the way?
No, I guess we took both semesters.
I should have thought about that a little bit.
And compared to high school, the English course, was it a demanding course?
Yeah, English was something that I made light of, I guess, in high school.
And so I made B's in 103 and 104 here, but it was a struggle.
Right, then...
Mainly because of time.
You know, in writing a theme, you had about enough time for one shot at it.
Not much polished time or anything else.
And what did you... Fred Eckfeldt was my English teacher, and that was really a blessing.
I didn't realize it at the time.
Describe him as a teacher.
Uh...
Very proper.
Of course, you know him, not a tall man, but very stately in his carriage and demeanor.
He was not, well.
What made him a good teacher?

I think his thoroughness in the fact that he wouldn't he wouldn't allow you to I just remember being him holding me holding me and then seeing him hold others to kind of their feet to the fire to give a give a reasonable answer he wouldn't just accept a whip or something like that
And yet he didn't do this in a way that you felt put upon or, I mean, he left you with your dignity, totally.
But he was a good role model to me in that he conveyed, imparted to me the fact that he considered
the business of writing and of composition to be important.
And you're working hard during these weeks and you're, did you go home in midsummer or just stayed here?
I had two trips that I can remember.
in the summer, and those were weekend trips.
I went home with, went to Baytown to the home of a twin, a couple of boys that were here that I had made friends with, the Banta brothers.
